&gt;Well, this may depend on the gradient of the fitness function. I
&gt;think Shimon&#39;s notion of task decomposition addresses this. 
&gt;Basically, you wouldn&#39;t want to try to evolve a robotic soccer team
&gt;against a high-performing hand-coded team, based just on
&gt;wins/losses/ties. Your evolving controllers will just lose every
&gt;time. But if you can successfully decompose the problem (which real
&gt;soccer players do), into distinct objectives (dribbling, passing,
&gt;shooting) you can incrementally build up skills and hopefully combine
&gt;them to solve holistic goals, such as winning a game.

I am quickly becoming convinced that this is not nessearily sesnsible to
do all at once. It makes sense to decompose the behaviours for one
network to learn into sub behaviours, but this doesn&#39;t seem scalable.
I&#39;ve been thinking about staging development of behaviours, and
modularly assembling specialized networks. 
What if a single network were trained for one well defined behaviour,
such as being attracted to bright objects. Then another network, using
the same inputs, were evolved to be afraid of fast moving objects. Then
connect both completed networks togoether, sharing the same input, and
evolve a connector network that balances the two behaviours.
This approach definitly follows the paradigm of task decomposition, and
is more like object oriented programming, and is not the idea of
&quot;letting the algorithm find the novel solution.&quot; On the flip side, it
could still be a very powerfull alternative to compact control systems,
like kens sounding rocket...

It&#39;s a thought, and I&#39;m sure other people have been thinking about
modularity.
Any comments?
chad 

